<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>

<chapter xml:id="ch14-storage-wars" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Storage Wars</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Before now we have only used small amounts of data that we typed in ourselves, or
      somewhat larger amounts that we extracted from Twitter. The world is full of other
      sources of data, however, and we need to examine how to get them into R, or at least
      how to make them accessible for manipulation in R. In this chapter, we examine various
      ways that data are stored, and how to access them.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-data-formats">
    <title>Data Formats: Open and Proprietary</title>

    <p>
      Over the last few years, the accelerating trend of Moore's Law has made data storage
      almost <q>too cheap to meter.</q> Although this opens many opportunities, it also means
      that people keep data around for a long time, and they may keep data around in many
      different formats. The world is full of different data formats, some of which are
      proprietary&#x2014;designed and owned by a single company such as SAS&#x2014;and
      some of which are open, such as the lowly but infinitely useful <q>comma separated
      variable,</q> or CSV format.
    </p>

    <p>
      One of the basic dividing lines in data formats is whether data are human readable or
      not. Formats that are not human readable, often called <term>binary formats</term>,
      are very efficient in terms of how much data they can pack in per kilobyte, but are
      also squirrelly in the sense that it is hard to see what is going on inside of the
      format. Human readable formats are inefficient from a storage standpoint, but easy to
      diagnose when something goes wrong.
    </p>

    <p>
      Among the most common formats:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><term>CSV (comma-separated values)</term>: A plain text format in which each
        field is separated by a comma. The first row often contains column names
        (headers).</p></li>
      <li><p><term>Tab-delimited</term>: Like CSV, but uses a tab character as the
        separator.</p></li>
      <li><p><term>Excel (.xls/.xlsx)</term>: A proprietary binary format owned by
        Microsoft that has become an informal standard for spreadsheet data.</p></li>
      <li><p><term>OpenDocument</term>: An open format, based on XML, that is used by
        programs like LibreOffice.</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-reading-files">
    <title>Reading Files into R</title>

    <p>
      The first and easiest strategy for getting data into R is to use the data import
      dialog in R-Studio. In the upper right-hand pane, the <q>Workspace</q> tab has an
      <q>Import Dataset</q> button that opens a dialog for reading text files. R-Studio
      tries to guess the appropriate separator and will give a preview of the data.
    </p>

    <p>
      At the command line, the most commonly used functions for reading text data are
      <c>read.csv()</c> for comma-delimited files and <c>read.delim()</c> for
      tab-delimited files:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch14-readcsv">
      <code>
myData &lt;- read.csv("myfile.csv", header=TRUE)
myData &lt;- read.delim("myfile.txt", header=TRUE)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      For Excel files, a general purpose data manipulation package called <c>gdata</c>
      provides essential facilities for importing spreadsheet files. Begin by installing
      and loading the package:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch14-gdata">
      <code>
install.packages("gdata")
library(gdata)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      The <c>gdata</c> package is a kind of <q>Swiss Army Knife</q> package containing
      many different functions for accessing and manipulating data. For example, R uses
      the value <c>NA</c> to represent missing data. Frequently, however, it is the case
      that data sets contain other values, such as 999, to represent missing data. The
      <c>gdata</c> package has several functions that find and transform these values to be
      consistent with R's strategy for handling missing data.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-database-access">
    <title>Connecting to Databases</title>

    <p>
      Many data sources, particularly databases, exist not as a single discrete file, but
      rather as a system that provides methods or calls to <q>query</q> data from the
      system. The <c>RODBC</c> package provides an Open Database Connection (ODBC)
      interface for Windows. For cross-platform database access, other packages such as
      <c>RMySQL</c>, <c>RPostgreSQL</c>, and <c>RSQLite</c> provide direct connections to
      specific database systems.
    </p>

    <p>
      A comprehensive access list of methods for obtaining data from a wide variety of
      programs and formats appears in the R Data Import/Export manual:
      <url href="http://cran.r-project.org/doc/manuals/R-data.html">http://cran.r-project.org/doc/manuals/R-data.html</url>
    </p>

    <p>
      As an open source program with many contributors, R offers a wide variety of methods
      of connecting with external data sources. This is both a blessing and a curse. There
      is a solution to almost any data access problem you can imagine with R, but there is
      also a dizzying array of options available such that it is not always obvious what to
      choose.
    </p>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch14">
    <title>Chapter Challenge</title>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-ch14-challenge">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Go to <url href="http://Data.gov">Data.gov</url> or another open data portal and
          find a data set in CSV or tab-delimited format that interests you. Download it and
          read it into R using either <c>read.csv()</c> or <c>read.delim()</c>. Use the
          <c>str()</c> and <c>summary()</c> functions to explore the structure of the data
          and report what you find.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch14">
    <title>Sources</title>
    <p>
      <ul>
